Most likely explanation: your “coherent chain above `m_graphicsData`” is stale bytes, not a live object.

The key source evidence is allocator-related:

- [MemoryBlockManager.cpp](/D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/shared/library/sharedFoundation/src/shared/MemoryBlockManager.cpp:397) shares allocators by `elementSize` when `shared=true`.
- [Direct3d11_PixelShaderProgramData.cpp](/D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/application/Direct3d11/src/win32/Direct3d11_PixelShaderProgramData.cpp:1022) installs its MBM with `shared=true`.
- [MemoryBlockManager.cpp](/D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/shared/library/sharedFoundation/src/shared/MemoryBlockManager.cpp:272) writes only the freelist `next` pointer into freed elements; the rest of the block remains old object bytes.
- [ShaderImplementation.cpp](/D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/library/clientGraphics/src/shared/ShaderImplementation.cpp:2754) does initialize `m_graphicsData(NULL)` and then calls `load()` before the factory assignment.

So: “address is in the PS-data MBM arena” does **not** prove it was freed by `~Direct3d11_PixelShaderProgramData` or `Direct3d11_PixelShaderProgramData::remove`. Shared MBMs are size-class arenas. A freed size-0x50 block can retain old `PersistentCrcString`, filename, refcount, etc. That exactly explains why `m_program`, `m_fileName`, and nearby fields look coherent while the first word is a freelist pointer.

The paradox has one hard constraint: if execution really reaches `m_graphicsData = Graphics::createPixelShaderProgramData(*this)` in [ShaderImplementation.cpp](/D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/library/clientGraphics/src/shared/ShaderImplementation.cpp:2770), the post-call store must happen. The source/factory signatures match: [Graphics.cpp](/D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/library/clientGraphics/src/win32/Graphics.cpp:1704) returns the pointer, and [Direct3d11.cpp](/D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/application/Direct3d11/src/win32/Direct3d11.cpp:666) returns `new Direct3d11_PixelShaderProgramData(...)`.

Therefore one of your assumptions is wrong:

- The watch was armed too late to see the initializer or pre-factory corruption. It was armed inside the RHS call, after `load(iff)`.
- Or the observed factory call is not returning to the assignment you think it is.
- Or the watch address/thread/context is wrong.
- But “the assignment ran and wrote nowhere” is not a viable C++ explanation.

I would **not** accept the vtable guard as the fix. It is a reasonable emergency crash fuse in [Direct3d11_StaticShaderData.cpp](/D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/application/Direct3d11/src/win32/Direct3d11_StaticShaderData.cpp:857), but it masks a stale owner pointer. If `2d_texture`’s program slot is stale, other post-FX/UI shaders allocated in the same region may render through fallback or skip material/reflection work silently.

The next experiment I’d run:

Set the hardware watch **before `load(iff)`**, at the first instruction in `ShaderImplementationPassPixelShaderProgram`’s constructor body, using the actual release `this` register/address:

```text
bp SwgClient_r!ShaderImplementationPassPixelShaderProgram::ShaderImplementationPassPixelShaderProgram
# when fileName == pixel_program/2d_texture.psh:
ba w4 (@this + 0x20)   # or the actual ECX-derived this+0x20 in x86
g
```

Then record every hit through constructor return. This pins whether `load_0000()` corrupts the slot before the factory, whether the post-call assignment stores somewhere else, or whether the debugger watch setup was misleading. If it trips inside allocator/free code instead, you have the real trigger stack.
